    <section>
        <strong>THE LONGEVITY OF OUR FIRST FATHERS WAS GIVEN IN YEARS, NOT IN MONTHS OR MOONS.</strong>
        <p> People exist who are try to deny the fact that our first fathers (Adam, Seth, etc.) used to live for
            centuries. They
            allege that the years mentioned in those chapters are really "months" or "moons". <strong>The only base for
                their
                absurd hypothesis is</strong> that if the number of years mentioned in the Bible for the antediluvian
            patriarchs
            ages is divided by 12, the result is a number of years <strong>"more acceptable" to them.</strong> As an
            example
            they show that if 930 years, the biblical age of Adam, is divided by 12 the quotient is 77 years. If
            Methuselah's
            age ( 969 ) is divided by 12 months the quotient is almost 81 years, and so on. <strong>When human beings
                want to
                deny God, or the authority of the Bible, they appeal to any nonsense, without using discernment, logic
                or
                scientific methods</strong>. Mankind made up this hypothesis and clothed it with the cloak of science.
            <strong>These
                "enlightened ones"</strong> who thought they found the "explanation" of the longevity of the patriarchs,
            didn't
            make any effort in reasoning even superficially the issue. That's why they charged against this passage
            wantonly and
            irresponsibly, thinking joyfully, that they have "discovered" a flaw in the Scriptures or in its
            interpretations.
            That is why they solemnly declare that in this passage the "so called" years, were just "moons" or "months".
            They
            declare all this without noticing that before their own eyes is the denial of their foolish hypothesis. Let
            us read
            Gen 5: 3-17.</p>
        <p> "3 <i>And <strong>Adam lived an hundred and thirty years, and begat a son</strong> in his</i> <i> own
            likeness,
            after his image, and called his name Seth.</i> 4 <i>And the days of</i> <i> Adam after he had begotten Seth
